  title =       "Instruction-level parallel processing",
  journal =     "Science",
  year =        "1991",
  REMOVE__number =      "253",
  REMOVE__pages =       "1233-1241",
  REMOVE__month =       sep,
  annotation =  "a very nice overview of ilp techniques.  software pipelining
    vliw, and data flow are all examined.  pipelining == transparent.
    limited to basic blocks == 2 - 3.5 speedup.  when interblock is done,
    5-20.  vliw is a transliteration of a desired record of
    execution which is feasible in the context of a given
    execution hw (has the disadvantage of being machin specific), superscaler
    does scheduling dynamically (ie invisible to compiler).  software
    pipeline == loop unrolling and then glomming iterations back into a
    kernel by overlapping them by some fixed offset.  trace directed
    scheduling uses profiling information to get critical path and
    distort the optimizing assumptions accordingly (ie. optimistic
    assumptions that can be rolled back if they go to hell).  predicated
    execution eliminates this."
}
