    booktitle= "Proceedings of the 19th International Symposium on Computer Architecture",
    REMOVE__month   =  may,
    REMOVE__pages = "256--267",
    year =        "1992",
  annotation =     "Basic observation: messages go through intervening buffers
    before arriving in user space.
    Basic idea: control information at the head of the mesg is the address
    of a user-level handler to extract the mesg.
    Order of magnitude more efficient than the mesg passing primitives
    provided.
    Key Optimizations: elimination of buffering.  Possible on receiving end
    because either storage for ariving data pre-allocated by user or
    the mesg can be serviced by a simple request.
    Deadlock avoidance is tricky: hinges on no blocking and `short' running
    threads.
    Comparision to J machine(s): fundamental difference between mesg driven
    model and AM is where the computation proper is performed.: computation
    in handlers (J) or in the `background' with handlers only removing
    packets.  J machine has trouble w/ locality (each mesg ~= 10 inst of
    work) and has an unbounded scheduling queue"
}
