@TechReport{schroeder:exp:grape,
  author =      "M.D. Schroeder and A.D. Birrell and R.M. Needham",
  title =       "Experience with {Grapevine}: the growth of a distributed system",
  institution =         "Xerox Parc",
  year =        1983,
  REMOVE__number =   "CSL-83-12",
  annotation =     "grapevine meant to scale by adding fixed power servers.
    registries are the primary method of organizing mappings,
    more users = more registeries (not larger ones).  hierarchy
    is used to combat scalability problems.  blindly organizing
    distribution lists by interest (a quantity that scales with
    the number of users) severly cramped the scalability of the
    system.  a lag in information propogation causes a tradeoff
    between the two desires of a transparent and
    computationally light-weight system.  hetrogeneous media provide
    tradeoffs that grapevine is not prepared to deal with.  like all
    dynamic systems the state of grapevine is difficult to ascertain,
    and the detail to which an implementor wants to know the condition
    of such a system has a direct impact on the computational overhead
    associated with state transitions. grapevine uses logs and a
    log viewing tool to detect problems, actions and their results."
}


